00:46:50.644 --> 00:46:54.484
enrichment in the young onset patients for these colibactin

787
00:46:54.524 --> 00:46:57.274
mutation signatures. So we're very confident that this is happening.

788
00:46:58.064 --> 00:46:59.694
So of course, the next question is, what does this mean?

789
00:47:00.164 --> 00:47:03.704
Why is this signature enriched in young onset patients?

790
00:47:04.524 --> 00:47:08.284
And so the first thing we did was to look at the genome, and it has been shown

791
00:47:08.344 --> 00:47:10.664
that there's a specific mutation in APC.

792
00:47:10.724 --> 00:47:14.164
Of course, APC loss is a near universal feature.

793
00:47:14.304 --> 00:47:18.124
Over 80% of colon cancers are initiated by an APC loss of

794
00:47:18.184 --> 00:47:20.984
function mutation that drives hyperactive Wnt signaling.

795
00:47:21.364 --> 00:47:23.464
But APC can be lost in many different ways.

796
00:47:23.774 --> 00:47:27.464
And there is one specific mutation which occurs in a splice

797
00:47:27.504 --> 00:47:31.384
site near the N-terminus of the APC gene, which occurs

798
00:47:31.444 --> 00:47:34.714
in fact, in that AT rich colibactin mutation signature

799
00:47:34.804 --> 00:47:38.614
context. And when we looked at this, indeed, we found an enrichment for this

800
00:47:38.724 --> 00:47:42.704
specific APC mutation across our patients who had the colibactin

801
00:47:42.744 --> 00:47:46.104
mutation signature. And what was really striking is that when we look at

802
00:47:46.524 --> 00:47:50.364
stratifying these patients by age of onset of their disease, the younger

803
00:47:50.424 --> 00:47:54.124
the patient is, the more likely their APC mutation and their

804
00:47:54.164 --> 00:47:57.934
tumor was to be in that colibactin mutation signature context.

805
00:47:58.244 --> 00:48:02.154
Suggesting that in the younger patients, the colibactin mutation was

806
00:48:02.204 --> 00:48:06.024
likely the initiating driver event for initiating these

807
00:48:06.064 --> 00:48:09.814
tumors. However, when we looked at the rest of the genome, we really didn't

808
00:48:09.884 --> 00:48:13.484
see any differences, no major differences in tumor mutation burden

809
00:48:13.544 --> 00:48:17.164
overall or copy number alteration in the colibactin signature

810
00:48:17.184 --> 00:48:20.544
positive or negative patients. And so this led us to

811
00:48:20.604 --> 00:48:24.044
hypothesize, in addition to inducing this mutation, could

812
00:48:24.084 --> 00:48:28.004
the colibactin toxin be doing something else

813
00:48:28.044 --> 00:48:30.594
to promote the progression of these cancers?

814
00:48:31.124 --> 00:48:34.688
So does colibactin mutagenesisimpact the phenotypic

815
00:48:34.748 --> 00:48:38.668
state of these tumors. And this has sort of reminded

816
00:48:38.748 --> 00:48:42.718
us of work that we've been doing in my lab, where we've really learned that

817
00:48:42.828 --> 00:48:46.268
as tumors progress from the normal colon to the primary tumor to the

818
00:48:46.288 --> 00:48:49.648
metastasis, these cancer cells, despite having the same

819
00:48:49.688 --> 00:48:53.628
mutations, acquire a sequence of cell state transitions

820
00:48:53.808 --> 00:48:57.768
that enable them to have increased plasticity, first into a highly

821
00:48:57.848 --> 00:49:01.548
conserved intestinal stem cell-like state, which is the cell state that the

822
00:49:01.608 --> 00:49:05.348
tumor cell population needs to be in in order for a mutation to turn into a

823
00:49:05.408 --> 00:49:09.288
tumor, and then eventually into increasingly more plastic states to allow

824
00:49:09.368 --> 00:49:12.488
adaptation during the metastatic process.

825
00:49:12.508 --> 00:49:16.428
And the mutations are the same, but these additional phenotypic changes

826
00:49:16.468 --> 00:49:19.588
confer increased ability to become aggressive cancer.

827
00:49:20.428 --> 00:49:23.008
And this is also happening in the context where we now know

828
00:49:23.948 --> 00:49:27.768
work from the Sanger in the UK has shown that across all adult human

829
00:49:27.828 --> 00:49:31.728
epithelial organs, including the gut, we know that by the time we get to

830
00:49:31.788 --> 00:49:35.068
adulthood, all of our epithelia harbor mutated cells.

831
00:49:35.238 --> 00:49:39.068
And in fact, we can find all of the oncogenic driver mutations, including those in

832
00:49:39.108 --> 00:49:42.688
APC, across completely morphologically normal

833
00:49:42.748 --> 00:49:46.308
appearing epithelia. So the mutation itself is necessary,

834
00:49:46.668 --> 00:49:50.128
but certainly not sufficient to drive the formation of a cancer.

835
00:49:50.408 --> 00:49:53.048
So this is what we were asking, could colibactin do more?

836
00:49:53.468 --> 00:49:56.738
To do this, of course, we needed a good model system, and we like to do things in

837
00:49:56.828 --> 00:50:00.688
human tissues. But the challenge here is that the bacteria has to

838
00:50:00.788 --> 00:50:04.188
stick to the lumen, into the apical aspect of the

839
00:50:06.008 --> 00:50:09.768
tumor or the epithelium in order to actually induce the

840
00:50:09.788 --> 00:50:13.758
mutagenesis. And the problem here is that when we use organoid culture,

841
00:50:13.808 --> 00:50:17.288
which is how we normally study these interactions,

842
00:50:17.728 --> 00:50:20.808
the apical aspect is on the inside of this tightly

843
00:50:21.048 --> 00:50:23.748
barrier-forming organoid. And so how do we get them in?

844
00:50:23.868 --> 00:50:27.548
We could microinject, very painful and not even really possible in mutated

845
00:50:27.608 --> 00:50:30.968
organoids, which actually do not often have big lumens.

846
00:50:30.988 --> 00:50:34.648
And so we took advantage of what we know about organoid biology, that the

847
00:50:34.688 --> 00:50:38.588
polarity of organoids is maintained by basal

848
00:50:38.628 --> 00:50:41.668
contacts of integrins expressed on the basal

849
00:50:41.908 --> 00:50:45.597
membrane of the epithelium with the laminins and

850
00:50:45.768 --> 00:50:48.688
other matrix proteins that are present in the matrigel.

851
00:50:49.108 --> 00:50:52.948
But we know that if we disrupt this barrier, as you can

852
00:50:53.008 --> 00:50:56.708
see here, the organoid can actually flip inside out on

853
00:50:56.748 --> 00:50:59.308
itself, basically inverting its polarity.

854
00:50:59.348 --> 00:51:03.008
And now the apical side, which is normally on the inside, is exposed on the

855
00:51:03.068 --> 00:51:06.748
outside. And so we took advantage of this to really create a

856
00:51:06.808 --> 00:51:10.518
model system where we could simply remove the organoids from

857
00:51:10.568 --> 00:51:14.448
matrigel and put them transiently in suspension culture to induce this

858
00:51:14.468 --> 00:51:18.448
flipping, the acrobatics of these organoids, to expose the apical

859
00:51:18.468 --> 00:51:22.228
lumen to the outside. We could then come along with a suspension of

860
00:51:22.248 --> 00:51:26.118
pks+ or delta-pks control bacteria that

861
00:51:26.348 --> 00:51:30.328
do not harbor the pks island that makes colibactin, and

862
00:51:30.348 --> 00:51:33.708
then we can flip them back. And indeed, we are able to do this.

863
00:51:34.528 --> 00:51:38.208
And when we add the bacteria, we see that these green GFP

864
00:51:38.248 --> 00:51:41.568
positive E. coli are now incorporated inside the

865
00:51:42.188 --> 00:51:42.968
lumen of the

866
00:51:44.588 --> 00:51:48.568
organoid, and they retain their viability in

867
00:51:48.628 --> 00:51:52.528
this context. And then basically what we did was to flip back and

868
00:51:52.608 --> 00:51:56.508
forth with this model system, to do long-term culture, to enable the

869
00:51:56.548 --> 00:52:00.518
mutations to be acquired and for the mutated cell population to be selected.

870
00:52:01.128 --> 00:52:04.817
And then we asked, indeed, could we see with whole genome sequencing,

871
00:52:04.848 --> 00:52:08.358
evidence of this mutation signature suggesting that this model actually works, that

872
00:52:08.388 --> 00:52:12.228
the bacteria were actually able to secrete the toxin, and the toxin could do

873
00:52:12.268 --> 00:52:16.248
its job in the system. And indeed, that's what we found, that we found when

874
00:52:16.288 --> 00:52:20.228
we look at controls that have either not undergone any of this flipping, week zero,

875
00:52:20.628 --> 00:52:24.528
or controls that have undergone flipping, but in the absence of bacteria or

876
00:52:24.568 --> 00:52:28.448
in the presence of delta-pks E. coli, so they experience all of the stress

877
00:52:28.488 --> 00:52:32.388
of being exposed to bacteria, lipopolysaccharide, et cetera, but

878
00:52:32.448 --> 00:52:35.528
not colibactin. And then finally, the pks+ E.

879
00:52:35.608 --> 00:52:37.808
coli that harbor the colibactin island.

880
00:52:38.668 --> 00:52:42.508
And when we do this, we see with whole genome sequencing that we see the

881
00:52:42.548 --> 00:52:45.668
colibactin signatures exclusively in the

882
00:52:46.248 --> 00:52:49.448
organoids that have been treated with the pks+ E. coli in this way.

883
00:52:49.808 --> 00:52:53.608
So this validates our model. And the next question we then asked

884
00:52:54.288 --> 00:52:57.668
was what happens with acute exposure to the bacteria?

885
00:52:57.748 --> 00:52:59.248
So now if we go back and expose the

886
00:53:00.528 --> 00:53:04.248
organoids to the bacteria just for 24 hours, what is the

887
00:53:04.308 --> 00:53:08.088
immediate response of the epithelial cell population

888
00:53:08.148 --> 00:53:12.058
to exposure to pks+ E. coli, controlling for this with

889
00:53:12.068 --> 00:53:15.748
delta-pks E. coli? So we are not looking at bacteria-specific effects, but

890
00:53:15.788 --> 00:53:17.588
simply colibactin-specific effects.

891
00:53:18.188 --> 00:53:21.988
And when we do this, we see upregulation with RNA-seq and proteomics

892
00:53:22.248 --> 00:53:23.188
of DNA repair

893
00:53:24.528 --> 00:53:28.228
associated programs. This is not surprising and again, serves as a nice control,

894
00:53:28.788 --> 00:53:32.538
because indeed, these organoids that are being exposed to

895
00:53:32.568 --> 00:53:36.148
the colibactin genotoxin are going to experience this

896
00:53:36.188 --> 00:53:37.328
mutagenic stress.

897
00:53:38.208 --> 00:53:41.708
And then we asked, what else could be going on

898
00:53:41.848 --> 00:53:44.208
here in terms of the phenotypic state?

899
00:53:44.608 --> 00:53:48.448
So what I already told you is that in order to make a tumor, the

900
00:53:48.468 --> 00:53:52.208
mutated cell must eventually enter into an intestinal

901
00:53:52.308 --> 00:53:56.008
stem cell-like state. And what this state is, is a cell state that

902
00:53:56.608 --> 00:54:00.568
normally exists in homeostatic intestines at the bottom

903
00:54:00.608 --> 00:54:04.388
of the intestinal crypts marked by LGR5 and other Wnt target

904
00:54:04.468 --> 00:54:08.368
genes. These are the cells that are capable of self-renewing and give

905
00:54:08.388 --> 00:54:10.888
rise to all of the daughter cells of the intestinal crypt.

906
00:54:10.908 --> 00:54:14.688
They divide and differentiate, and actually every five days or so, we have an

907
00:54:14.728 --> 00:54:18.608
entirely new gut lining. And so, the cells

908
00:54:18.628 --> 00:54:21.828
that divide and differentiate are eventually lost into the lumen of the gut.

909
00:54:22.328 --> 00:54:26.268
But the self-renewing population is this LGR5 population at the base

910
00:54:26.308 --> 00:54:30.068
of the intestinal crypt. So in order for a tumor to

911
00:54:30.128 --> 00:54:33.798
occur, we need to have, of course, this APC tumor-initiating

912
00:54:33.868 --> 00:54:37.508
mutation. That can happen in the LGR5 cell itself,

913
00:54:37.698 --> 00:54:39.548
that can then serve as a cell of origin.

914
00:54:39.908 --> 00:54:43.268
But alternatively, we now know that the gut is a very plastic

915
00:54:43.908 --> 00:54:47.658
organ, and if you get that mutation in a differentiated cell type,

916
00:54:48.508 --> 00:54:52.308
if that cell type is now able to dedifferentiate and switch

917
00:54:52.348 --> 00:54:56.168
back into an LGR5 cell, that is also capable

918
00:54:56.228 --> 00:54:59.948
of inducing a tumor. So this was the question we were asking, could

919
00:54:59.968 --> 00:55:03.748
colibactin mutagenesis, in addition to inducing an APC

920
00:55:03.788 --> 00:55:07.588
mutation in some cases, could that also be doing something to influence the

921
00:55:07.608 --> 00:55:11.588
cell state to drive these cells into a more pro-tumorigenic state?

922
00:55:12.468 --> 00:55:16.268
And when we did this, we looked with single-cell RNA-seq at our organoids that had

923
00:55:16.288 --> 00:55:19.048
been treated with pks+ or delta-pks E. coli.

924
00:55:19.418 --> 00:55:22.488
And indeed, we found that even though all these organoids

925
00:55:22.548 --> 00:55:26.188
expressed stress signatures, which is not surprising given that they're being

926
00:55:26.228 --> 00:55:28.088
exposed to bacteria and LPS,

927
00:55:28.908 --> 00:55:32.708
there was an enrichment, surprisingly, of the intestinal stem cell program

928
00:55:33.388 --> 00:55:36.488
in the pks+ E. coli treated organoids.

929
00:55:36.648 --> 00:55:39.128
This was really surprising because most other stresses we

930
00:55:40.088 --> 00:55:43.988
give these organoids actually push them away from the stem cell state into a

931
00:55:44.048 --> 00:55:46.308
more injury repair regenerative state.

932
00:55:46.348 --> 00:55:50.264
And in fact, we see the opposite here.We also see upregulation of

933
00:55:50.284 --> 00:55:53.704
markers that are well characterized of this Wnt-driven intestinal stem cell stage,

934
00:55:54.064 --> 00:55:57.964
including Lgr5 and Ascl2. And we can see this both

935
00:55:58.004 --> 00:56:00.524
in tumor organoids that we treat with pks+ E.

936
00:56:00.564 --> 00:56:04.514
coli, as well as from our normal colon organoids from a

937
00:56:04.604 --> 00:56:08.394
number of different patient donors, suggesting that this is really a shared

938
00:56:08.544 --> 00:56:09.164
biology.

939
00:56:10.024 --> 00:56:11.424
Functionally, what does this mean?

940
00:56:11.804 --> 00:56:14.264
So we can assess functional stem cell function

941
00:56:15.144 --> 00:56:19.084
by seeding cells from organoids as single cells, and these

942
00:56:19.124 --> 00:56:22.804
cells must then dedifferentiate and switch into an Lgr5 stem cell state

943
00:56:23.164 --> 00:56:25.704
in order to form and regenerate new organoids.

944
00:56:26.064 --> 00:56:29.834
And again, we found that when we treated the organoids with pks+

945
00:56:30.184 --> 00:56:33.904
E. coli, we saw increased functional stem cell

946
00:56:33.964 --> 00:56:37.944
ability, the increased ability to form new organoids relative to when

947
00:56:37.984 --> 00:56:40.344
we treated the organoids with the Δpks E.

948
00:56:40.404 --> 00:56:43.884
coli, suggesting again, a functional enrichment of this

949
00:56:44.004 --> 00:56:46.344
Lgr5 expressing stem cell program.

950
00:56:47.204 --> 00:56:51.084
This also resulted in long-term increased proliferation in the

951
00:56:51.104 --> 00:56:54.904
pks+ E. coli treated organoids. And then we asked,

952
00:56:55.084 --> 00:56:58.424
how is this happening? How is this working mechanistically?

953
00:56:58.434 --> 00:57:02.324
And to ask this question, we teamed up with the lab of Ileana Cristea at

954
00:57:02.344 --> 00:57:06.284
Princeton, and we were able to do a technique called TPC

955
00:57:06.484 --> 00:57:10.064
mass spectrometry. So this is thermal protein co-aggregation mass spectrometry,

956
00:57:10.664 --> 00:57:12.284
which involves basically,

957
00:57:13.344 --> 00:57:17.084
when exposed to pks+ or Δpks E. coli, what we

958
00:57:17.144 --> 00:57:20.784
now do is to treat the cell as a bag of protein-protein

959
00:57:20.864 --> 00:57:24.724
complexes, and we can melt these protein complexes by treating

960
00:57:24.784 --> 00:57:28.604
the cell suspension at different temperatures and then running mass spec,

961
00:57:28.924 --> 00:57:32.644
with the idea being that more stable protein-protein complexes will

962
00:57:32.724 --> 00:57:36.404
melt at higher temperatures than less stable protein-protein interaction

963
00:57:36.504 --> 00:57:40.344
complexes. And in this way, we can look at what are the protein complexes

964
00:57:40.624 --> 00:57:44.384
that are preferentially stabilized only in the presence of pks+

965
00:57:44.584 --> 00:57:46.764
E. coli and not in the presence of Δpks.

966
00:57:47.164 --> 00:57:51.144
And here again, when we do this approach, we see again enrichment of the DNA

967
00:57:51.164 --> 00:57:55.094
repair complexes. But intriguingly and really strikingly, we also

968
00:57:55.164 --> 00:57:58.603
see at this resolution chromatin remodeling complexes.

969
00:57:58.624 --> 00:58:02.004
And when we look at what chromatin remodeling complexes are being formed, these are

970
00:58:02.104 --> 00:58:05.944
all repressive complexes, complexes that are involved in turning

971
00:58:06.044 --> 00:58:09.024
off gene expression. So what could this mean?

972
00:58:09.664 --> 00:58:13.464
So to understand that better, we then performed ATAC-seq on our organoids.

973
00:58:14.044 --> 00:58:17.544
This looks at chromatin accessibility, in pks+ versus

974
00:58:17.604 --> 00:58:21.524
Δpks organoids. And again, we see across the

975
00:58:21.564 --> 00:58:24.424
entire genome, we see a decrease in chromatin

976
00:58:24.444 --> 00:58:27.584
accessibility in the pks+ E. coli treated

977
00:58:27.644 --> 00:58:31.204
organoids. When we looked now at the motifs of

978
00:58:31.214 --> 00:58:35.154
transcription factors that are capable of binding to these lost peaks,

979
00:58:35.804 --> 00:58:39.744
this is now when we really had an aha moment, because what was really

980
00:58:39.784 --> 00:58:43.624
striking without even looking at the specifics of the transcription factors, are

981
00:58:43.644 --> 00:58:47.264
the sequences of their motifs. We saw that the motifs that were repressed

982
00:58:47.604 --> 00:58:51.444
were largely AT-rich, whereas the motifs that were opened

983
00:58:51.484 --> 00:58:54.764
and enhanced in accessibility in this context were largely

984
00:58:54.804 --> 00:58:58.624
GC-rich. And indeed, this AT-rich motif reminded us, of

985
00:58:58.664 --> 00:59:01.084
course, of the colibactin mutation signature.

986
00:59:01.184 --> 00:59:04.774
This is where colibactin binds and can mutate, but

987
00:59:04.784 --> 00:59:08.154
perhaps also does more than just mutate and does more in terms of

988
00:59:08.164 --> 00:59:12.084
repression. And indeed, the top gene, whose transcription

989
00:59:12.164 --> 00:59:15.464
factor binding motif was repressed in pks+ E.

990
00:59:15.504 --> 00:59:19.124
coli, was Cdx2. And this was really impressive and

991
00:59:19.164 --> 00:59:22.684
intriguing for us because Cdx2 is a transcription factor that we

992
00:59:22.744 --> 00:59:26.284
need to make the entire intestinal differentiation program.

993
00:59:26.664 --> 00:59:30.314
So repression at this locus suggests that the cell is turning

994
00:59:30.424 --> 00:59:33.544
off the differentiation program, and by default, then

995
00:59:33.624 --> 00:59:35.844
dedifferentiating into a stem cell state.

996
00:59:36.244 --> 00:59:40.064
And indeed, when we looked at the Cdx2 specific targets, we see

997
00:59:40.304 --> 00:59:42.144
a decrease in accessibility there.

998
00:59:42.404 --> 00:59:45.964
We've also now done Cdx2 cut and run to show that the direct binding of

999
00:59:46.004 --> 00:59:49.914
Cdx2 is impaired when the cells are treated with pks+

1000
00:59:50.224 --> 00:59:50.724
E. coli.

1001
00:59:51.544 --> 00:59:55.264
And then we also were able to do some AlphaFold 3 structural modeling.

1002
00:59:55.304 --> 00:59:58.654
And we tested the hypothesis in silico, that

1003
00:59:58.744 --> 01:00:02.184
Cdx2 binds here to the minor groove of

1004
01:00:02.224 --> 01:00:05.884
DNA at these AT-rich regions. And then when we

1005
01:00:05.944 --> 01:00:09.603
modeled colibactin, that fitted beautifully into that exact

1006
01:00:09.644 --> 01:00:13.344
same binding site for Cdx2, suggesting that there could be

1007
01:00:13.384 --> 01:00:16.664
direct competition between colibactin binding and the

1008
01:00:16.704 --> 01:00:20.484
displacement of Cdx2 from its promoters in the

1009
01:00:20.524 --> 01:00:22.944
minor grooves of AT-rich regions in the genome.

1010
01:00:23.424 --> 01:00:25.384
The same thing was also true for Hoxb13.

1011
01:00:25.464 --> 01:00:29.104
Hoxb13 is a transcription factor that is not expressed in the adult

1012
01:00:29.264 --> 01:00:33.204
gut, but it is expressed during gut development and is required for gut

1013
01:00:33.224 --> 01:00:36.584
development. And perhaps this plays a role in early

1014
01:00:37.344 --> 01:00:40.144
exposures in the neonatal period.

1015
01:00:41.084 --> 01:00:44.924
When we went back to patient samples which had whole genome sequencing,

1016
01:00:45.344 --> 01:00:49.224
we were also able to find enrichment of these same transcription

1017
01:00:49.264 --> 01:00:52.844
factor binding motifs at the same sites where we found colibactin

1018
